.\" Manpage for gyc.
.\" Contact ecadorel@gmail.com to correct errors or typos.
.TH man 1 "15 May 2018" "1.0" "gyc man page"
.SH NAME
gyc \- A GCC-based compiler for the Ymir language
.SH SYNOPSIS
gyc [\fB\-c\fR|\fB\-S\fR] [\fB\-g\fR]
    [\fB\-O\fR\fIlevel\fR]
    [\fB\-I\fR\fIdir\fR...] [\fB\-L\fR\Idir\fR...]
    [\fB\-m\fR\fImachine-option\fR...]
    [\fB\-o\fR \fIoutfile\fR] [@\fIfile\fR] \fIinfile\fR...

.SH DESCRIPTION
.IX Header "DESCRIPTION"
The \fBgyc\fR command is a frontend to \fBgcc\fR and supports many of the same options. This manual only documents the options specific to \fBgyc\fR.

.SH OPTIONS
.IX Header "OPTIONS"
.SS "Input and Ouput files"

.IX Subsection "Input and Ouput files"
The file name suffix determines what kind of compilation is done. The following kinds of input file names are supported :
.IP "\fIfile\fR\fB.yr\fR" 4
.IX Item "file.yr"
Ymir source files.
.PP
You can specify more than one input file on the \fBgyc\fR command line, in which case they will all be compiled. If you specify a \&\f(CW\*(C`\-o \f(CIfile\f(CW\*(C`\fR option, all the input files will be compiled together, producing a single output file, names \fIfile\fR.
.SS "Options for Directory Search"
.IX Subsection "Options for Directory Search"

These options specify directories to search for files, libraries, and other parts of the compiler :
.IP "\fB\-I\fR\fIdir\fR" 4
.IX Item "-Idir"
Specify a directory to use when searching for imported modules at compile time. Multiple \fB\-I\fR options can be used, and the paths are searched in the same order.

.IP "\fB\-L\fR\fIdir\fR" 4
.IX Item "-Ldir"

Specify a directory when searching for libraries at linking time, as with \fBgcc\fR.

.IP "\fB\--iprefix\fR \fIprefix\fR" 4
.IX Item "-iprefix prefix"
Specify \fIprefix\fR as the prefix for the gcc directory containing target-specific Ymir sources.

.IP "\fB\--standalone\fR" 4
.IX Item "standalone"
Do not search the standard system directories for Ymir source files. Only the directories that have been specified with \fB\-I\fR options (and the directory of the current file, if appropriate) are searched.

.SH SEE ALSO
gcc(1)
